# Architecture

Build a reusable world engine, not one-off scene code.

## Principles

- Keep files small.
- Favor composition.
- Prefer reusable components over hardcoded meshes.
- Never let `App.tsx` become large — it should stay a thin entry point.
- Build primitives first, then compose higher-level concepts.
- Generate worlds from data; do not hardcode large scenes.
- Organize code into components, data, types, and utilities.
- Avoid over-engineering.
- Build one milestone at a time.
- Each change should leave the app running.

## Folder structure

```txt
src/
  components/
    primitives/   # Floor, Wall, Door, Window, Box, simple furniture
    world/        # Canvas, scene assembly, lighting setup
    house/        # Room, House, FloorPlan
    player/       # Camera, movement, controls
  data/           # Layout and world definitions
  types/          # Shared TypeScript interfaces
  utils/          # Geometry, positioning, layout helpers
```

## Good vs bad

```tsx
// Good — reusable, data-friendly
<Room width={16} depth={20} height={9} />
<Wall length={16} height={9} position={[0, 4.5, -10]} />
<Furniture type="couch" position={[2, 0, 4]} />

// Bad — entire scene hardcoded in App.tsx
```

## Important constraint

Do not manually model the whole house.

The house should be generated from code and data.
